These rules establish consistent conventions for CSS classes, HTML IDs, ARIA attributes, and file structure to ensure code clarity, modularity, and accessibility.

## I. CSS Class Naming Rules (The BEM Methodology)

The Block, Element, Modifier (BEM) methodology is the standard for CSS class naming.

| Rule ID | Convention | Structure | Description |
| :---: | :---: | :---: | :--- |
| **R1** | **Case Standard** | `kebab-case` | Use all lowercase letters, separated by hyphens (e.g., `user-profile`). |
| **R2** | **Block Name** | `.block` | The standalone, reusable component (e.g., `.button`, `.header`, `.modal`). |
| **R3** | **Element Name** | `.block__element` | A part of the Block, separated by a **double underscore (`__`)** (e.g., `.button__icon`). |
| **R4** | **Modifier Name** | `.block--modifier` | A state or variation, separated by a **double hyphen (`--`)** (e.g., `.button--primary`, `.button--disabled`). |
| **R5** | **Purpose-Driven** | Avoid location or visual names. | Names must describe *what* the component is (e.g., `.error-message`), not *how* it looks (e.g., `.red-text`). |
| **R6** | **Specificity Avoidance** | Reserved for JS/A11y | **DO NOT** use `#IDs` for styling; reserve them for JavaScript hooks or accessibility references. |

